{"title_page": "Addtech", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|{{advert|date=October 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=September 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name  = Addtech AB\n|type  = [[Public company|Publicly traded]] [[Aktiebolag]]\n| foundation  =  The original company Bergman & Beving was founded 1906. In 2001 Addtech was listed on the NASDAQ OMX Stockholm exchange.\n| location  =  [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| key_people  = Niklas Stenberg [[CEO]]\n| industry  =  Technology trading\n| num_employees =  approx. 2900\n| revenue=  [[Swedish krona|SEK]] 10 billion (2018/2019 Annual report)\n| homepage = [http://www.addtech.com www.addtech.com]\n}}\n'''Addtech''' is a Swedish, listed technology trading group. Addtech consists of approximately 130 subsidiaries with in total about 2,900 employees. The Group is active within selected niche markets for high-tech products and solutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/company/ADDTB:SS|title=AddTech AB - Company Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} The customers are to a large extent Nordic companies within the manufacturing industry. The Group has yearly sales of SEK 10 billion and sells to ca 30 countries.   \n \n==Business Areas==\nOperations are organized in five business areas: Automation, Components, Energy, Industrial Process and Power Solutions.{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Addtech Automation''' sells intelligent solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}, subsystems and components, primarily for industrial automation and infrastructure, including solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} for robotics, control systems, sensors, industrial networks and communication networks.\n\n'''Addtech Components''' sells components and solutions within the areas of mechanics, electromechanics, hydraulics and electronics. Customers mainly operate in the segments of machinery production, special vehicles, energy and electronics in the Nordic manufacturing industry. \n\n'''Addtech Energy''' Energy sells products for the transmission and distribution of electricity, as well as products in the areas of electrical safety, electrical installation and connection technology. Customers operate mainly in the energy and electrical installation market.\n\n'''Addtech Industrial Process''' Industrial Process sells solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}, subsystems and components that contribute to optimising industrial process flows. Customers operate mainly in the northern European manufacturing and processing industries.\n\n'''Addtech Power Solutions''' Power Solutions develops and sells components and solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} for power supply and for steering and controlling movements or energy flows. Customers operate mainly within special vehicles, the energy sector and the electronics industry.\n\n==Market==\nAddtech\u2019s operational focus is on the [[Nordic countries]], although markets outside the region have grown in importance in recent years. The operations beyond the Nordics are in the UK, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Poland, Estonia, Latvia, Japan, USA and China. In addition to this, the Group exports to more than 20 other countries.\n\n==History==\nAddtech originates from the company '''Bergman & Beving''' which was founded in 1906 and went public in 1976. The division of operations into business areas, and the combination of decentralization and own responsibility, were already catchwords at the time of Bergman & Beving, and has laid the foundation for the business philosophy of today's Addtech. In 2001, Bergman & Beving divided operations in three independent subsidiaries each of which is listed on the [[Nasdaq OMX Stockholm]], also called [[Stockholm Stock Exchange]]. Three new companies were born; Bergman & Beving, now [[B&B Tools]], Lagercrantz Group and Addtech. Since Addtech's listing in 2001 approximately 90 corporate acquisitions have been made.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Stockholm Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Sweden]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 1906]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|{{advert|date=October 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=September 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name  = Addtech AB\n|type  = [[Public company|Publicly traded]] [[Aktiebolag]]\n| foundation  =  The original company Bergman & Beving was founded 1906. In 2001 Addtech was listed on the NASDAQ OMX Stockholm exchange.\n| location  =  [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| key_people  = Niklas Stenberg [[CEO]]\n| industry  =  Technology trading\n| num_employees =  approx. 2900\n| revenue=  [[Swedish krona|SEK]] 10 billion (2018/2019 Annual report)\n| homepage = [http://www.addtech.com www.addtech.com]\n}}\n'''Addtech''' is a Swedish, listed technology trading group. Addtech consists of approximately 130 subsidiaries with in total about 2,900 employees. The Group is active within selected niche markets for high-tech products and solutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/company/ADDTB:SS|title=AddTech AB - Company Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=03/04/2020}}</ref>{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} The customers are to a large extent Nordic companies within the manufacturing industry. The Group has yearly sales of SEK 10 billion and sells to ca 30 countries.   \n \n==Business Areas==\nOperations are organized in five business areas: Automation, Components, Energy, Industrial Process and Power Solutions.{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Addtech Automation''' sells intelligent solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}, subsystems and components, primarily for industrial automation and infrastructure, including solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} for robotics, control systems, sensors, industrial networks and communication networks.\n\n'''Addtech Components''' sells components and solutions within the areas of mechanics, electromechanics, hydraulics and electronics. Customers mainly operate in the segments of machinery production, special vehicles, energy and electronics in the Nordic manufacturing industry. \n\n'''Addtech Energy''' Energy sells products for the transmission and distribution of electricity, as well as products in the areas of electrical safety, electrical installation and connection technology. Customers operate mainly in the energy and electrical installation market.\n\n'''Addtech Industrial Process''' Industrial Process sells solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}}, subsystems and components that contribute to optimising industrial process flows. Customers operate mainly in the northern European manufacturing and processing industries.\n\n'''Addtech Power Solutions''' Power Solutions develops and sells components and solutions{{solution-inline|date=October 2019}} for power supply and for steering and controlling movements or energy flows. Customers operate mainly within special vehicles, the energy sector and the electronics industry.\n\n==Market==\nAddtech\u2019s operational focus is on the [[Nordic countries]], although markets outside the region have grown in importance in recent years. The operations beyond the Nordics are in the UK, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Poland, Estonia, Latvia, Japan, USA and China. In addition to this, the Group exports to more than 20 other countries.\n\n==History==\nAddtech originates from the company '''Bergman & Beving''' which was founded in 1906 and went public in 1976. The division of operations into business areas, and the combination of decentralization and own responsibility, were already catchwords at the time of Bergman & Beving, and has laid the foundation for the business philosophy of today's Addtech. In 2001, Bergman & Beving divided operations in three independent subsidiaries each of which is listed on the [[Nasdaq OMX Stockholm]], also called [[Stockholm Stock Exchange]]. Three new companies were born; Bergman & Beving, now [[B&B Tools]], Lagercrantz Group and Addtech. Since Addtech's listing in 2001 approximately 90 corporate acquisitions have been made.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Stockholm Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Sweden]]\n[[Category:1906 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 1906]]\n", "name_user": "Unknown.editor777", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edited citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addtech"}
{"title_page": "Joan Crawford filmography", "text_new": "{{short description|A list of film appearances of American actress Joan Crawford}}\n[[File:Joan Crawford in The Last of Mrs Cheyney trailer.jpg|thumb|Crawford in ''[[The Last of Mrs. Cheyney (1937 film)|The Last of Mrs. Cheyney]]'' (1937)|alt=]]\n[[File:Joan Crawford in The Women trailer 2.jpg|thumb|right|Crawford in ''[[The Women (1939 film)|The Women]]'' (1939)]]\n[[File:Joan Crawford in Mildred Pierce trailer.jpg|thumb|right|Crawford in ''[[Mildred Pierce (film)|Mildred Pierce]]'' (1945)]][[File:The Damned Don't Cry! 1.jpg|thumb|right|L-R: Crawford, [[Steve Cochran]], [[Richard Egan (actor)|Richard Egan]], and [[David Brian]] in ''[[The Damned Don't Cry]]'' (1950)]]\n[[File:Bette Davis and Joan Crawford in Whatever Happened to Baby Jane trailer.jpg|thumb|right|Crawford and [[Bette Davis]] in ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962)]]\n\nThe '''Joan Crawford filmography''' lists the film appearances of American actress '''[[Joan Crawford]]''', who starred in numerous [[feature film]]s throughout a lengthy career that spanned nearly five decades.\n\nShe made her film debut in ''[[Lady of the Night]]'' (1925) as a [[body double]] for film star [[Norma Shearer]]. She appeared in several other films before she made her major breakthrough playing [[Lon Chaney]]'s love interest in the 1927 [[horror film]] ''[[The Unknown (1927 film)|The Unknown]]''. Her major success in ''[[Our Dancing Daughters]]'' (1928) made her a popular [[flapper]] of the late 1920s. Her first sound film ''[[Untamed (1929 film)|Untamed]]'' (1929) was a critical and box office success.\n\nCrawford would become a highly popular actress throughout the 1930s, as a [[leading lady]] for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]. She starred in a series of \"[[rags to riches|rags-to-riches]]\" films that were extremely popular during the [[Great Depression|Depression]]-era, most especially with women. Her popularity rivaled fellow MGM actresses, including [[Greta Garbo]], [[Norma Shearer]] and [[Jean Harlow]]. She appeared in eight movies with [[Clark Gable]], including romantic drama ''[[Possessed (1931 film)|Possessed]]'' (1931), musical film ''[[Dancing Lady]]'' (1933), romantic comedy ''[[Love on the Run (1936 film)|Love on the Run]]'' (1936) and romantic drama ''[[Strange Cargo (1940 film)|Strange Cargo]]'' (1940) among others.<!-- Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ (1925)\nThe Merry Widow (1925)\nPossessed (1931)\nDance, Fools, Dance (1931)\nLaughing Sinners (1931)\nScreen Snapshots (1932)\nDancing Lady (1933)\nForsaking All Others (1934)\nChained (1934)\nLove on the Run (1936)\nStrange Cargo (1940)\nhttp://www.imdb.com/search/title?roles=nm0001076,nm0000022&title_type=feature,tv_episode,video,tv_movie,tv_special,mini_series,documentary,game,short\n --> In 1937, she was proclaimed the first \"Queen of the Movies\" by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine, but her popularity soon waned. After her films ''[[The Bride Wore Red]]'' (1937) and ''[[Mannequin (1937 film)|Mannequin]]'' (1938) proved to be expensive failures, in May 1938, Crawford \u2013 along with [[Greta Garbo]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Kay Francis]] and many others \u2013 was labeled [[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]; an actor whose \"box office draw is nil\".\n\nCrawford managed to make a comeback in the comedy ''[[The Women (1939 film)|The Women]]'' (1939) opposite an all-star female only cast. On July 1, 1943, Crawford left MGM and signed an exclusive contract with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Brothers]], where she became a rival of [[Bette Davis]]. After a slow start with the studio, she received critical and commercial acclaim for her performance in drama ''[[Mildred Pierce (film)|Mildred Pierce]]'' (1945). The film earned her an [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. From 1946 to 1952, Crawford appeared in a series of critical and box office successes, including the musical drama ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946), film noirs ''[[Possessed (1947 film)|Possessed]]'' (1947, for which she received a second Academy Award nomination) and ''[[Flamingo Road (film)|Flamingo Road]]'' (1949), drama ''[[The Damned Don't Cry]]'' (1950) and romantic comedy ''[[Goodbye, My Fancy]]'' (1951) among others. She received a third \u2013 and final \u2013 Academy Award nomination for her performance in the thriller ''[[Sudden Fear]]'' (1952).\n\nIn 1953, Crawford starred in the musical ''[[Torch Song (1953 film)|Torch Song]]'', her final film role for MGM. Her next film ''[[Johnny Guitar]]'' (1954) although not a major hit, is one of Crawford's most popular films among her fans. During the latter half of the 1950s, Crawford starred in a series of [[B-movie]]s, including romantic dramas ''[[Female on the Beach]]'' (1955) and ''[[Autumn Leaves (film)|Autumn Leaves]]'' (1956). In 1962, Crawford was teamed with [[Bette Davis]] in a film adaptation of ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]''. The [[thriller film]] was a box office hit, and briefly revived Crawford's career. Her final film performance was in the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[science fiction film]], ''[[Trog]]'' (1970).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Feature films===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|+ Silent films\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Director\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Studio\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[Lady of the Night]]'' || Double for [[Norma Shearer]]<ref name=\"uncredited\">Uncredited</ref> || [[Monta Bell]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[Proud Flesh (film)|Proud Flesh]]'' || Party Guest<ref name=\"uncredited\" /> || [[King Vidor]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[A Slave of Fashion]]''<sup>\